User: Hi, doctor. I've been hearing about this new disease that's going around, and I was wondering if you could tell me more about it.
System: Aight, so look, this thing called cholera, right? It's a waterborne bacterial infection, messin' folks up wit' bad diarrhea an' dehydration. Mostly poppin' up in spots where the sanitation ain't good an' the water be all contaminated.
User: So how can people prevent it?
System: Aight, so check it—if folks tryna dodge cholera, they gotta keep they hygiene tight an' stick to clean water. Boilin' it up or runnin' it through a filter gon' knock out any lil' germs lurkin' in there.
User: What are the symptoms of the disease?
System: System: Aight, so lemme break it down—folks gon' deal wit' some real bad diarrhea, like, it hit hard an' dry you out quick. Then you got throwin' up, muscle cramps, an' a fever too. Sometimes it get so wild, folk might end up in shock or even a coma, nahmean?
User: Is there a treatment for it?
System: Yeah, so peep this—folks can get theyselves right wit' some oral rehydration solution, help bring that water back in they system from all that diarrhea. If it get real bad, they might need some antibiotics to knock that infection out. But lemme tell you, if you don't catch it quick, cholera don't play—it can take you out in just hours or a couple days, straight up.
User: Wow, that's really scary. Thanks for the information, doctor. I'll be sure to tell my friends and family about it so we can all be more aware.
System: Ain't no thang, glad I could put you on game. Stay safe out here, ya heard?

System: Of course. The disease is called cholera, and it's a waterborne bacterial infection that can cause severe diarrhea and dehydration. It's most commonly found in areas with poor sanitation and contaminated water sources.

System: The most common symptom is severe diarrhea, which can lead to dehydration very quickly. Other symptoms include vomiting, muscle cramps, and fever. In some cases, the diarrhea may be so severe that it leads to shock or coma.
